Just a couple tips for working with sugar... wear cloth gloves under your rubber gloves. Sugar burns are horrible, and your rubber gloves will do very little to protect your hands. Taking a wet paintbrush and painting the sides of your pan will help to avoid the re-crystilization of the sugar. When your sugar starts to boil, place a steel bowl, or something similar, over the top of your pot. This will speed up the melting of your sugar, and help the temperature rapidly increase, as well as creating condensation so you don't have to keep brushing the sides of the pan with water. A digital laser thermometer works just as well as, and sometimes better than a candy thermometer. To get rid of your bubbles after boiling, graze the top of your molten sugar with a blowtorch, this will pop most of your bubbles instantaneously, so you don't loose the thin viscosity of the molten sugar so it stays easy to pour and work with. Also, to get rid of your tails, heat them with your blowtorch and cut them off with scissors. It is much cleaner, and much easier.
